result.execSummary:
The defendant Carol D Luckett was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Carol D Luckett in court with attorney Mary D Scholle.  Grant Huebner appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by counsel and defendant.  
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 75 days in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 2 days time served.  The court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 12 months with the following conditions:
*Defendant to serve 75 days  in the House of Correction.  No good time credit.  Court stayed sentence to be used at the agent's discretion. 
*Seek and maintain fulltime employment.
*Obtain high school diploma or GED.
*Cognitive Behavior Therapy
*Vocational/educational training, if appropriate
*Defendant to complete 25 hours of community service.
*Pay supervision fees.

Court ordered defendant to pay DNA surcharge.
Defendant to pay DNA surcharge and all other costs and surcharges during probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

Filed,
-Notice of Right  to Seek Postconviction Relief.
